Tue Jul 6, 2026

So, today is my first day studying SICP.

I initially planned to thoroughly and carefully read through the entire book 
over the summer break. However, after a quick skim, I realized that's 
impossible---especially since I have to spend a lot of time every day working 
out and writing other side projects. So, I've decided to take my time.

The entirety of Section 1.1 mostly covers basic programming concepts and Lisp 
syntax. It's very straightforward, but there are definitely quite a few 
gotchas. For instance, you can't just write '-x' in Lisp; you have to write 
'(- x)'. This is because Lisp doesn't define '-' as an operator like other 
languages do. Instead, it behaves more like a procedure (or a function).

And here are a few interesting facts:

* Tail-Call Optimization: The Lisp interpreter (at least the one used for 
  teaching in SICP) features special tail-call optimization. Consequently, 
  a function that would normally cause a stack overflow, like this:

    void recursion(void)
        return recursion();

  ...will run perfectly fine in Lisp. However, if there is a pending 
  operation involving a value within the function call, the interpreter 
  still has to allocate a separate stack frame, meaning it will still 
  overflow.

* Indentation & Formatting: The Lisp community generally prefers using two 
  spaces for indentation. Furthermore, spaces are used for alignment to keep 
  the layout looking clean and beautiful.

  For example:
    
    (define (abs x)
      (cond ((= x 0) 0)
            ((> x 0) x)
            ((< x 0) (- x))))

I've found that SICP can be a bit of a pain, but learning it is strangely 
addictive.
